				<table width="100%" cellspacing="5">
				<tr>
					<td>
					

						<div class="postbody"><div class="quotetitle">Quietust wrote:</div><div class="quotecontent">One specific thing to notice is <em>why</em> node 10094 is powered by default. If you jump to node 12942 and then look immediately to the right, you will see a purple rectangle that's part of 10094 which is connected to VCC on the left and <em>itself</em> on the right (the poly has a small &quot;hook&quot; on the right which connects directly to the bit of diffusion using a &quot;buried contact&quot;, which is a via between poly and diffusion). That particular bit is effectively a <em>pull-up resistor</em> (it's actually a transistor whose threshold voltage is below GND, leaving it permanently enabled); if you look around the chip, you will see <strong>hundreds</strong> of them scattered all over the place, most commonly in places that have registers.</div><br /><br />Guessing the point of that is to prevent VCC and ground from being shorted together when any of the gates are open, though I still don't see exactly how the resistor works  <img src="./images/smilies/icon_confused.gif" alt=":?" title="Confused" />. Good to know that that's what those are at least. Do you get a pull-down resistor if you put the resistance next to ground instead?<br /><br />Is there some place I can add node names by the way?</div>

					<br clear="all" /><br />

