			</td>
			<td valign="top">
				<table width="100%" cellspacing="5">
				<tr>
					<td>
					

						<div class="postbody"><div class="quotetitle">ulfalizer wrote:</div><div class="quotecontent">Guessing the point of that is to prevent VCC and ground from being shorted together when any of the gates are open, though I still don't see exactly how the resistor works  <img src="./images/smilies/icon_confused.gif" alt=":?" title="Confused" />.</div><br />The actual transistor itself is very thick (the distance between the VCC on the left and the yellow on the right), and that gives it a high resistance - if you look at other transistors, you'll notice that they are extremely thin.<br /><br /><div class="quotetitle">ulfalizer wrote:</div><div class="quotecontent">Do you get a pull-down resistor if you put the resistance next to ground instead?</div><br />No, because you never actually do that in NMOS - the only reason you use those kinds of pullups is because &quot;normal&quot; pull-up transistors are slow and weak in NMOS (they're only used with tristate logic where a node needs to be either driven low, driven high, or left floating, such as t15823 for reading $4015.0); if you want proper pull-up transistors, you make them PMOS (which makes the chip CMOS).</div>

					
						<div class="postbody"><br />_________________<br />Quietust, QMT Productions
<br />P.S. If you don't get this note, let me know and I'll write you another.</div>
